			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-07-16T13:38:43+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">July 16, 2014 9:38 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">July 16, 2014 9:38 am</span>		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">GoodÂ WednesdayÂ morning from Washington. Heat and humidity are taking a brief hiatus, but there will be no such relief for relations between President Obama and House Republicans.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In fact, Mr. Obama might need to make sure his legal counsel is on hand. Speaker John A. Boehner forges ahead Wednesday with his plan for aÂ <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/07/17/us/politics/boehner-lawsuit-obama-health-care-law.html" target="_blank">lawsuit against the president</a>Â over his use of executive powers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Although the legal challenge was inspired by an array of executive actions that Mr. Obama has taken as part of what the administration has called a &#8220;year of action,&#8221; the lawsuit will focus on the presidentâs handling of the implementation of the health care law. Republicans charge that Mr. Obama has broken the law by delaying penalties on businesses that donât offer health insurance to their workers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Obama called the threat of a lawsuit an act of stagecraft this week when he said, âTheir big idea has been toÂ sueÂ me.Â  Thatâs what theyâre spending time on, a political stunt that wastes Americaâs time and taxpayer dollars.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The House Rules Committee willÂ <a href="https://rules.house.gov/bill/113/h-res-PIH-President-Litigation" target="_blank">debate the merits of a lawsuit</a>Â atÂ 10 a.m. The hearing will feature testimony from Elizabeth Price Foley, a law professor at Florida International University, who is expected to make the case that the lawsuit could succeed.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Hereâs what else you need to know:</p>
<ul>
<li>Mr. Obama is not shying away from his plans to address climate change. He willÂ <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/07/17/us/politics/white-house-unveils-climate-change-initiatives.html?hp&amp;action=click&amp;pgtype=Homepage&amp;version=HpSum&amp;module=second-column-region&amp;region=top-news&amp;WT.nav=top-news" target="_blank">unveil a series of initiatives Wednesday</a> aimed at guarding the electricity supply; improving local planning for flooding, coastal erosion and storm surges; and better predicting landslide risks as sea levels rise and storms and droughts intensify.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>The Department of Veterans Affairs remains under the microscope.Â <a href="//www.veterans.senate.gov/hearings/the-state-of-va-health-care07162014" target="_blank">At aÂ 10 a.m.Â Senate hearing</a>, Sloan D. Gibson, the acting V.A. secretary, will offer the latest on the state of the embattled agencyâs health system.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Scientists for the Centers for Disease ControlÂ <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/06/20/health/up-to-75-cdc-scientists-may-have-been-exposed-to-anthrax.html?module=Search&amp;mabReward=relbias%3Ar%2C%7B%221%22%3A%22RI%3A6%22%7D" target="_blank">faced a scare</a>Â last month when potentially infectious anthrax samples were sent to labs that were not equipped to handle them. AtÂ 10 a.m.,Â Dr. Tom Frieden, director of the C.D.C., will explain to theÂ <a href="//energycommerce.house.gov/press-release/hearing-notice-subcommittee-oversight-and-investigations-examine-anthrax-incident" target="_blank">House Energy and Commerce Committee</a>Â how this could happen.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>It will be a busy day for watchers of the United States economy. Janet L. Yellen, chairwoman of the Federal Reserve, provides testimony for the second consecutive day, this time before the House Financial Services Committee, atÂ 10 a.m. The Fed also releases its Beige Book report of regional economic snapshots atÂ 2 p.m.Â Separately, Douglas W. Elmendorf, director of the Congressional Budget Office, will detail the long-term budget outlook for theÂ <a href="//budget.house.gov/hearingschedule2014/hearing7162014.htm" target="_blank">House Budget Committee atÂ 10 a.m.</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Hereâs what weâre reading:</p>
<ul>
<li>Gov. Chris Christie is getting ready toÂ <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/07/16/us/politics/christie-to-test-presidential-hopes-in-iowa-trip.html?hp&amp;action=click&amp;pgtype=Homepage&amp;version=HpSum&amp;module=first-column-region&amp;region=top-news&amp;WT.nav=top-news" target="_blank">test his presidential hopes</a>Â again with a three-city swing through Iowa. After six months of scandal, the visit is his highest profile foray into the presidential arena. (New York Times)</li>
<li>Meanwhile, Iowaâs Senate race isÂ <a href="//www.nbcnews.com/politics/first-read/dead-heat-iowa-senate-race-democrat-leads-new-hampshire-battle-n156701" target="_blank">shaping up to be a nail-biter</a>. A new poll shows the Republican Joni Ernst and the Democrat Bruce Braley tied with 43 percent of registered voters each. (NBC)</li>
<li>Mr. Obama and German Chancellor Angela Merkel finally broke the ice. The two had theirÂ <a href="//online.wsj.com/articles/president-obama-speaks-with-germanys-merkel-1405474125" target="_blank">first conversation</a>Â since Germany expelled the Central Intelligence Agencyâs station chief amid spying allegations. They discussed intelligence cooperation and Ukraine. (Wall Street Journal)</li>
<li>Unsurprisingly, Hillary Rodham Clintonâs presidential aspirations came up during her visit to Jon Stewartâs &#8220;The Daily Show.&#8221; While she did not make any proclamations,Â <a href="//onpolitics.usatoday.com/2014/07/15/hillary-clinton-jon-stewart-president-2016/" target="_blank">she did offer that she prefers a âhome officeâ</a>Â to a commute and that one with âfewer cornersâ would be preferable. (USA Today)</li>
</ul>
	</div>
